Not only that, from the start the staff was very welcoming and informative. They gave me peace of mind and answered all my questions. My brother has so many underlying conditions. Going into Barlow with a tracheotomy was not easy to accept for any of us. But Barlow was the right place for him! Barlow weened my brother off the ventilator, they provided wound care, they gave him speech therapy, and RNA therapy. The nurses were very kind to him. Nurse Ana from second floor, THANK you for always keeping me updating and staying on top of my brothers healthcare! Thank you to Ariel, Anastacia, Dr. Eng, Dr, Ramirez, Dr. Way, Hector (RNA therapist), Rafael, Dr. Brailey, Dr. Nelson AND the entire staff for doing such a wonderful job! My brother has now been transferred over to a sub acute in Santa Monica and where his care is being continued. They will continue to provide his therapies and we will soon be able to bring him home with or no trach. These last almost 4 months have felt an eternity but God is with us and we are so thankful to the Barlow staff! -The Martinez Family< /Text>< Resp>

< Name>
Catherine Gallant</Name>
<Time>1594324656533<//Time>< rate>
5< /rate>
<Review>Should you or a relative need a respiratory hospital, Barlow is the best place for treatment.  My husband was in the ICU of a local medical center and required a ventilator to breathe.  He needed advance care to help regain use of his lungs and I wanted to be sure he was treated at a facility which had the best possible outcomes.  After much research, I did my darndest to make sure he would be transferred to Barlow and I have not had one second of regret.

My husband was a "hot mess" when he was admitted to Barlow Respiratory Hospital, including bacterial infections and a previously untreated wound, all of which needed to be addressed before his lungs could start their journey back to health.  In short order the infectious disease specialist and wound specialist took care of these setbacks and the respiratory therapists were waiting to start their work.  The staff at Barlow will not give up on a patient - my husband is a quadriplegic (which adds another fly to the ointment) and had a couple of starts and stops in his ventilator "weaning". Each time, the respiratory therapy staff restarted the process and today he is strong enough to breathe 12+ hours per day without the ventilator and increasing every day!!!

In addition to the doctors and respiratory staff, I must send a huge shout out to the nursing staff.  They provide wonderful care to my husband and we are very impressed with their skills and commitment to patient care. Communication in the age of COVID-19 is difficult. I can't be at the hospital asking questions, but the nurses are terrific. When I, or my daughter, call for an update, usually we are able to speak with a nurse immediately.  In the rare instances when my husband's nurse for the day is unavailable at that moment, we always receive a call back in a timely manner.  Always.  Additionally, we are able to speak with my husband during the day and evening via FaceTime  (or WhatsApp for non Apple users). We never feel as if we are interrupting and everyone is courteous, helpful and genuinely pleasant to deal with.  I'm sorry that I do not mention staff by name but I don't want to leave anyone out as all have been phenomenal!!!

My husband also receives occupational and physical therapy.  As I mentioned, he is a quadriplegic.  One day last week I received an unexpected FaceTIme from his p/t. My husband was able to lift his legs a bit (first time on his own!) and the p/t thought my husband might want to FaceTime me to celebrate. Best call ever!

Finally, I would be remiss if I did not send kudos to Bethany, the Social Worker with whom I deal regularly on everything from disability paperwork to my husband's emotions.  She is very accessible and on top of the needs of both the patient and family members. When Bethany sensed I was overwhelmed by my husband's issues, she set up a zoom meeting for my daughter and me so that we could "meet" the staff treating my husband and ask any questions on his status and treatment plan.  When I had additional questions following the meeting, Bethany followed up with the appropriate staff members.  She cares and goes "above and beyond"!

I made the right choice - Barlow Respiratory Hospital is the best!</Review>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>

< Review>
My Mom, Gloria, had the good fortune of being at Barlow Hospital not only once but twice!  Both times we were fortunate that she was taken care of by Dr. Nelson and his excellent team.  During her first stay Dr. Nelson made the prudent decision to give her time to wean from the ventilator, and a tracheotomy was avoided.  After another critical illness almost four years later, my Mom was again at Barlow and received the care that she needed to get back on her feet.  Not only was the physical care good but the staff was warm and reassuring.  Dr. Nelson arrived every morning to check on her progress and even combed her hair.  The nurses and aides responded promptly, and there were some that even sang!  The therapists were great too, and many of the staff remembered her from the last time she was there.  A former sanatorium from the days of tuberculosis, the historic buildings are nestled in a lovely valley with gardens, a koi pond and even flocks of parrots flying through.  In an age when large, impersonal hospitals are becoming the norm, Barlow offers high quality medical care in a unique setting, with personal attention and kindness!</Review>

Some of the staff here are genuinely abusive to the patients.  I have 3 witnesses to this behavior.  They are dangerously understaffed, and unsanitary. They hide the bad reviews and they drug their patients with multiple psychoactive drugs in order to keep them from complaining.  It is really a very sad situation.  Many of their patients can't talk because they are on a ventilator.  A nurse told me a lot of the patients are out of it, but now that I see that they handle complaints by drugging their patients I imagine some of them weren't admitted in that state.  The family has no idea what's going on in many cases because the doctors do not communicate medication changes.  I had an outside doctor review my loved one's medication list and they found that the amount of psychoactive drugs being given (especially since there was never any history of needing it prior) was excessive and could cause cognitive damage.  Please spare your loved one this abuse and avoid Barlow at all costs.  If your loved one isn't an easy case they won't see them through the weaning process even though they advertise that they do. We've been coming here for about 7 years now. It's been going down hill especially in the last few years. The hash browns used to be magical! Now they just aren't even good anymore. <Time>1572199258225< /Time><rating>2</rating>< Text>
I stayed at the Hard Rock Hotel for 5 days and had breakfast at Maryjane's for 3 days out my 5 day stay. The breakfast was great (especially their potatoes and bacon)...however, after eating breakfast there on day 4, I left the restaurant to later return a hour later to drink coffee and do a little computer work, only to be told I could not be seated without ordering food due to the "expected" lunch crowd. I explained that I ate breakfast there a couple of hours earlier and just wanted to sit, drink coffee and work on my laptop for a couple of hours. Being that they have a separated bar area in the resturant and the restaurant and bar were not full in addition to my eatting there earlier, I assumed it would not be a problem. However, the hostess denied me the opportunity to be seated but after I wasn't easily turned away and continued with questions, the hostess decided to ask the manager to speak with me.  The manager, Lily Jones, came over and preceded to give a similar explanation, which was starting to sound a lot like discrimination, being that they could not give me a solid justifiable reason as to why they could not seat me, even if only for an purchased cup of coffee or tea. After going back and forth about the issue with the manager, Lily, she finally decided that it would be ok for me to sit at the bar and work and order coffee. Although, the bartender who attended to me, was extremely kind, attentive and provided amazing customer service, the previous interaction with the hostess and manager made my experience after being seated uncomfortable to the point to where I left shortly after I was seated. With thst being said, I will not return to Maryjane's.</Text>

< Text>
The food here is ridiculously expensive. Honestly $13 for pancakes is absurd. However... the food is really good for a little diner type place in a hotel. I also had a hamburger and fries. $16 for that. Shockingly expensive. BUT! Really good and more food than I could eat in two sittings. <user_name>Brian Bergstr√∂m< /user_name>< time>

< Rating>
3< /Rating>
<Text>While taking lunch from working at Comic-Con we crossed the street to eat at the themed SyFy Cafe. Open tables were everywhere, yet we were forced to wait 10 minutes of out of our lunch time to get a table out on the patio with no shade.

It took another 10 minutes for the waitress (Abbott the Rabbit)  to come acknowledge us, so we informed her we were in a hurry and ordered food with our drinks.

When the food came it was pretty much correct, I had ordered well done and it was medium-well, but I can deal with that. we were sharing the $19 bacon cheeseburger. We asked for BBQ sauce for the burger and some ranch for the fries. We were in a hurry to get back to work and know the mess crossing the street so we started eating... we saw our waitress casually attending to other tables for several minutes and we were almost finished when another server finally brought out the BBQ and Ranch. I never even had the opportunity to try the BBQ on my burger before finishing it...

When the bill came the charges were...

$19 Cardioburger
$2   Split Plate
$1   BBQ Sauce
$.50 Ranch
$1.97 Tax

Total $24.47 for a burger and fries.... so grand total with tax and tip... $24.47 as I didn't have time to argue with the waitress over these charges I simply let her pay for them with her deserved gratuity.

Easily the most expensive yet mediocre burger I have ever had.< /Text>< pics>
None< /pics>

<name>Benjamin Cherry<//name><time>1490893248455</time>< Rate>
2<//Rate>
< review>
The moment I walked in I was greeted by a friendly younger woman with dark hair, dark makeup and tattoos -- think the friendliest goth kid from high school. I took a seat the bar and she gave me a menu. So far, so good.

Then, the waiting. I asked twice for coffee (first to the hostess, and then to the bartender) and it took an excruciating 5? 10? minutes for me to get a cup of joe. My hope, and frankly, my expectation is that coffee at the bar in a breakfast place should be reflexive. Not the case here.

Then, the food. God, the food was terrible. I got the cake and eggs: pancakes from batter in a box, cheapest sausage links I've had since summer camp (and cold), and worst of all -- WORST OF ALL -- Mrs. Butterworth's. Are you f****** kidding me? This is not even maple syrup, this is just "syrup." Chris Rock can tell you what that's for, and isn't pancakes.

So, the staff was lovely and saved whatever semblance of a breakfast experience this was going to be. The food was offensive and I'll never be back.< /review>

Real Compassion & understanding are vital during this pandemic.  There are no words to describe the pain one suffers after losing a family member and being unable to be with those suffering most.  I'm in Florida and my daughter & son-in-law are in Fresno. They just lost their unborn daughter of 7 months. My husband & I both fall into vulnerable categories and are unable to travel and be there to bring personal comfort to them or even attend the funeral. < username>
Shane Stokes</username>
<Rate>4<//Rate><user_id>111110288719611798933< /user_id>< Review>
Pretty good for the area. They give you a little more than you expect but not close to the male salons of LA or NYC, this is NOT the old school barber experience but many steps up from Supercuts, Great Clips and the rest of the 20 dollar fare. The staff is nice and know what they are doing but they do have a few stylists that need a bit more training. Had many cuts here and been great for the most part which is why I continue to come here. It's taken me a minute to figure who is best here but this knowledge guarantees a great cut. One last thing, this placed is always booked, especially on weekends so get to app or call to book an appt or you will not get in. I gave it 4 stars for the lesser skilled stylists and because the experience could still step it up (A full time receptionist, coffee/mocha options, etc) but it's been the most consistent in the Roseville area and still a better value than other salons in the area.</Review>

<Rating>5</Rating>< Text>
Great selection of musical instruments from their mainstay used guitars to school band instruments.  They'll order stuff they don't have, but they have the best selection in cheap but good used guitars and other modern musical instruments.  We've bought and sold guitars, amps, pedals, mics, cables, and rack equipment.  It's always fun to tool around and see what's in stock or read the wall covered with upcoming gig posters.  They were great on Ocean, now they're down on Pacific, the heart of town, so parking is limited unless you're willing to pay.  And that's okay!<//Text>

<user>109011699302249023791< /user><review>Little by Little is a true hidden gem at the Warm Springs district in Fremont, CA, close to where T4 is. They are tucked away in the corner of the shopping center and this place serves really delicious food! They currently only do to go orders only and all the staff members do their very best to maintain covid safety procedures. They do fusions of every cuisines and serve from pastas, sandwiches, rice plates, and sides. I really enjoyed their food so much that I 100% truly recommend the most! I got to try their vegetarian options which were the roasted garlic cauliflower truffle Mac and cheese, the rainbow salad, and mushroom coconut pesto curry.

I will review the roasted garlic cauliflower truffle Mac and cheese first! It was absolutely my favorite dish on the menu! The presentation of the Mac and cheese was beautiful with the breadcrumbs on top and the chives to give it a nice color. Literally I haven‚Äôt had Mac and cheese in so long and this brings back many memories but I liked this version MUCH BETTER! I love the addition of the truffle oil because I think it gave a nice fattiness to the dish but it wasn‚Äôt drenched in oil which that‚Äôs a good thing. The breadcrumbs gave the Mac and cheese great texture and I love the dish having some garlic as well. I actually do wish that the Mac and cheese was cheesier because Mac and cheese is supposed to be a cheesy dish and for me, I personally wanted more cheese not only to make a viral tik tok video but taste wise, I would have liked and tasted more cheese. I also didn‚Äôt see a lot of cauliflower unless it was cut up small which I appreciate so you don‚Äôt get huge chunks but I didn‚Äôt  taste cauliflower. Overall, my favorite dish on the menu hands down, I really recommend the Mac and cheese!

The rainbow salad is basically kale, baby spinach, red quinoa, cherry tomatoes, red cabbage, roasted white corn, crispy quinoa, with yuzu aioli, and gribiche sauce on the side. This was truly a rainbow salad! I saw a lot of color and the presentation of the salad was beautifully done! You get the freshness of the kale, spinach and love all the vegetables and fruits in the salad as well! The nuttiness of the quinoa was delicious which added a nice flavor aspect to the salad. On the dressing, I‚Äôm questioning why I got two dressings because normally  we would only see one dressing so the dressings don‚Äôt clash. I wish I only got one dressing instead of two different dressings but both of them tasted about the same in terms of flavor. If I were to choose, I feel like the yuzu aioli was better in terms of flavor and thickness. I thought the gribiche sauce was too thick for me but the yuzu aioli felt lighter; still a but thick but tasted better in my opinion.

The mushroom coconut pesto curry has button mushrooms, red quinoas, cauliflower, corn, and garlic rice. I loved the flavor of the coconut curry. I thought it was creamy, smooth, light, and it was mild. I also love the addition to the quinoa because that added flavor and texture. The mushrooms, I love too and that is like a substitute for meat so the seasoning was on point and definitely was fulling to eat. With the cauliflower, again I didn‚Äôt get a lot of cauliflower. I wish there was more and I wish the rice had more garlic because I didn‚Äôt get a lot of garlic. Overall, I‚Äôm super satisfied with this curry and loved all the elements of the curry!

Overall, Little by Little in Fremont is a true hidden gem in Fremont! I really recommend it and please support this business! They have put a lot of heart and soul to the food and the chef was great in putting everything together to make the dish perfect!<//review><user_name>Jupiter Devours- Maelynn Le< /user_name><date>1614538664391<//date>< resp>

<user_name>Regina Wu<//user_name><Date>1579397863518</Date><rate>4< /rate>< Text>
What a hidden gem in Warm Springs. I have passed by this place for so many times without notice it.

We decided to give it a try on a beautiful weekend. Small restaurant but completely filled up on Saturday noon.

The food here is so delicious and the drinks are cute too.

Order:
Roast Bone Marrow: Personally I love the bone marrow a lot, and the sauce on the side is phenomenal.
Seared Scallops: the seared scallops are spot on, and love the creative side of shrimp chili oil.
Confit duck leg: Love the harmony of crispy duck skin and the tender duck meat!

Drinks:
Rose lemonade is delicious!

Thanks for the complimentary spiced popcorn and definitely come back next time to explore more options.</Text>

Super weird location but pleasantly surprised by the overall experience. All of the farm to table dishes were fantastic. This place has a great chef - that's for sure. The surprising dish was the chuck steak. By the looks of it, one would guess it was overcooked and dry - but really is tender and full of flavor. The pasta for the pappadelle taste like they hand made it; very fresh. Only complaint would be lighting was a tad bit on the bright side - I feel like they could do okay with being 30% less lumen.< /review>

<text>Incredible food by an incredible chef. Go experience the awesomeness.</text><Name>Jeoffrey Guevara<//Name><rate>5< /rate>< Pics>
None</Pics>
< Date>
1546397378598< /Date>
</record></dataset><record>
< Text>
It's about time Fremont gains a new restaurant with class.

The core cuisine is American & French tapas. The menu is subject to change and it's been suggested that foie gras might be served in the future.

The most notable items I had here was the bone marrow, short rib, and uni pasta.

The bone marrow is served with some bread and it's basically a pate. Very rich and flavorful, would be a great choice if you're looking for brunch.

The short rib's presentation is lovely, like a meadow encircled by a dark forest. The meat just falls apart with a slight push of the fork. The garnish adds a complexity to the meat's succulent texture and a small bite of the salad followed by the meat helps balance the flavors. It is by far my favorite dish as it is both a feast for the eyes and the mouth.

The uni pasta here is sure to convince anyone apprehensive of trying uni. The uni itself turns the dish practically into macaroni and cheese, but it doesn't have the smell or heaviness of cheese. The uni is light and custardy and goes great with the roe on top of the pasta. It almost tastes like a comfort food, but has the flavors of the sea incorporated into it. Definitely recommended.

Will come back soon to see how the menu evolves.</Text>

<GmapID>0x808fc65b8df00001:0xc5005cf459a6b782< /GmapID></record>

<review>I came here for date night on a Friday evening without a reservation. I've learned that I should make a reservation next time in order to secure one of the few tables.

I ended up sitting by the bar which is not bad in any way as you get a good view on the kitchen and can see how everything is being prepared. I observed how the chef takes great pride in finishing off every dish before he sends it out and is focused on quality and a consistent experience.

Having that said, the dishes do look pretty and very presentable. I tried 4 dishes, plus desert and every dish was worth a photo. The first one I had was the Octopus dish. It's supposed to be a shareable dish, but the portion is still rather small and you only get a few bites of Octopus. All of that is fine in general, the issue is the prize. You pay over $20 for that dish and if you want to feed two people well, you need to order at least three more dishes - if not even four more. This means you will end up paying between $100-170 including drinks. I am ok to pay this kind of money for a nice dinner, but I expect the right service and taste then. Let me elaborate on this.

All dishes I had tasted solid, but there was nothing that really blew me away. Some dishes, like the Risotto are a great idea, but the flavor is not yet there where it needs to be. It felt too salty to me and too soft. I think it's a matter of time and the chef will turn this into a great dish.

Similar with the bone marrow. It's something that you don't eat every day and it was certainly well cooked. But it was missing that certain something that makes me want to end up spending so much money on it. For example, it comes with basic toast which feels just very boring.

The short ribs were solid as well, but not tender and juicy enough for the prize.

Again, there's nothing wrong with the food, but I think the chef just needs some time to refine and work on the recipes to justify the high charge.

The service was so-so. I've ordered a glass of the Cabernet from Passo Robles. One of my favorite wine regions and the red did not disappoint. But: they charge $12 a glass which is somewhat standard in the Bay area, but I never got poured less wine in a glass than here. It almost felt I get more wine when I go to a wine tasting. When I tried to bring this up with the waiter in a friendly and funny way and told him that I love this wine, he just mentioned he would let the chef know. I also asked if the Yelp check-in for 50% off cocktails would apply to wine, because I would take another glass if it would - he said no. I had two sips of the wine and the glass was empty. When I paid and was ready to leave, the waiter offered me another glass on the house - very wrong timing.

Overall the service was very friendly though and I ended up leaving a nice tip.

The place itself feels upscale, modern and cool. It could almost be in L.A. I feel it has huge potential but requires some serious work on the food, the prizes and the wine.</review><user_id>107651363527543844794<//user_id>< Name>
Jonas Gebhardt< /Name>

<text>I never expected that visiting a smog shop could put me in a better mood than I was before, but my experience at Smog Busters was just so unexpectedly pleasant, it couldn't help but lighten my mood.

I happened to be in the Roseville area and Google'd smog shops to see what I could find on my way home.  Smog Busters was the first one I called.  I asked how much a smog check would be and the price I was quoted was a little lower than I expected.  This was my first time smogging our all wheel drive Dodge Charger and I knew that it couldn't be put on the dyno like shops usually do during a smog check, so I asked how much MORE that would cost me.  Even though it was clear that I expected it to cost more because of this, the gentleman who answered the phone (one of the owners) then informed me that he would actually take another $5 off the price because those were a little easier for him to do! It was a PERFECT opportunity for him to make some extra money on my smog check; not only did he NOT take advantage of me, he further discounted his, already low, prices!

So, I dropped by Smog Busters shortly after our phone call.  The facility was nice and clean and staff (owners) were friendly.  I was out of there in a matter of minutes.

<Text>I was recently taken here during one of the lowest points of my life. I did not want to live and so I was sent here for observation. I thought I would be able to talk to some therapists one on one, but that is not what this place is. Canyon Ridge basically holds people there so that they will not hurt themselves, and that is all. I kept asking for a therapist to talk to, and the nurse would say they would get someone, but no one ever came. I suffer with social anxiety, so when they told me to join the groups, I couldn't think of anything worse. Why would I want to divulge the most humiliating and devastating thing that ever happened to me to a group of strangers? You only get to talk to the psychiatrist for a couple of minutes because they have so many patients to go through. He put me on anti-depressants and told me to join the groups. The third day I was there I decided to sit in one of the groups and I was glad that I did. Eventually I started joining as many of the groups that pertained to me and I found people to talk to and have fun with. That part was very healing as opposed to isolating myself to my room. Some parts of the hospital are very clean, but they do need to update their bathrooms. The bathrooms are filthy. My shower curtain had black mold on it, and the shower would not drain. Also, fruit flies came flying out when I would move the curtain aside. It is difficult to sleep because people are coming into your room every ten minutes or so to check on you, and basically shine a flashlight in your face, which I find really disrespectful. I had one of the workers sitting outside my room all night coughing, rustling papers, or clicking her pen. Let people sleep!! Other than that, the cafeteria food was pretty decent, which was surprising. If you are going to go here, I suggest joining the groups and making sure to eat regularly. It can be a healing place if you let it.< /Text><Pictures>None</Pictures>< Resp>

<review>I honestly hate to give this place a one star review.
A bit over 1 year ago.

I had reached a breaking point in my life. A lot of people do. I had a Psychological break down.

I was taken from the emergency room to Canyon Ridge. The employees were not cruel or malicious however they did not seem to enjoy their job most of the time. Fair enough, you are working in a Psych Ward, I referred to it as an Adult Daycare because that is entirely how it felt. I was checked on every 5-10 minutes, even while sleeping which was difficult because it would wake me up often in the middle of the night.
Loved ones begged me to listen to the Psychiatrist and try the medication he provided. The medication failed miserably. When the nurse who checked on me noticed, she did nothing to assist me, understand why I was on the floor shaking, or even report it.

Throughout my stay there under the 51/50, they constantly would send their largest male nurse to confront me about refusing to get in the medication line and I had to repeatedly tell the nurses about the experience the medication caused and they continued to not record it and pressured me to shut up and take the damn pill. I had to learn to "No." to doctors and nurses whom clearly don't know better and don't care.

Which is one reason why the experience was god awful but I wouldn't change that because it forced me to become stronger, however, most people don't function with that mentality so it is a horrible situation to be in and need to learn to grow up and stand for yourself.

The other patients were actually far more supportive and kind as opposed to talking with the Psychiatrist which had no time to talk. Out right said "If you aren't here to find a drug to help you fix yourself, then there is nothing more we can do for you." They do not have the staff to support therapist talks, they entirely rely on the other patients to help the other patients. That was made very clear to me.

However, as the few days went by, people got released and the new set of individuals whom were brought in flooded the facility and we started to have people with clear and alarming mental derangement, some of which would hiss or attempt to attack staff or other patients.

I was in the suicide and drug addiction ward, that's not a normal type of person in that ward. That is someone who requires full time staff attention and should not be in any general public.

Some of the nurses were actually kind and saw me as just another human, they understood that it was just one really bad day and one really bad judgement call I made that landed me there, but not all the nurses were like that.

So the reason for one star is largely I feel that there are unquestionable better locations that are not over populated, understaffed, underpaid. It is a dice roll for your loved one if they get sent there under a 51/50 or even bring themselves there.

I don't hold the employees in contempt, but I am going to do my damnedest to never be sent back to any place like a Psych Ward ever again because of the over all experience.

For the people such as David, Gina, Maizy, Axle, Robert, gosh I can barely remember the other names of all the people whom I talked with in the group talks and 1 on 1. They were the people that helped me find myself again and right myself. The location however leaves so much to be desired.

I don't give it 1 star with joy, but because I know if it wasn't for the other patients I interacted with, it would have been a horrible experience. Their food is okay, they have a soda machine which is awesome, but if I want free soda and a wild emotional swing in my life, I'll just go to a god damn casino.

For any nurse that might actually for some weird reason remember my name, or the group therapist leader, I can't remember her name to save my life. You were not the problem, however, you and I both know there are not enough like you employed at that location to be a successful solution. Nor is there enough money to make that the case.</review><pictures>None<//pictures></record>

<userid>103679260964735039600< /userid><user_name>Emmflowers<//user_name><time>1534009008211<//time>< Rating>

<text>This place helped me save my life at its lowest moment. We were encouraged to spend our days outside of our rooms and into common areas inside and outside. It is of benefit to communicate with the other patients (we avoided anything grim or gritty) and learned how people from so many different walks of life had ended up there.
There were group activities every hour for 6 hours during the day including physical activity in a separate gym area. A TV room, an outside (small grasses area) patio. Three meals a day in a separate fairly large buffet style cafeteria and snacks an additional 2-3 times a day. These snacks depended on your individual nutritional needs. There was laundry on site. Two-bed rooms with private shower. You were allowed a couple of 10 minute phone calls a day to check in with family or whomever.
On the medical side, there were group counseling sessions, an individual case manager, a nutritionist, psych techs who passed meds and collected daily vitals, and of course the (rarely seen) doctor. At night they did walkthroughs every 15 minutes. I felt safe and supported and stayed 2 extra days until I felt sure I was okay. I trusted them with my life and I‚Äôm here because they jump started my now current treatment. Thank you. April 2016<//text>< Pictures>
None<//Pictures>

This was never disclosed to us as parents.  Our adolescent was there to be "helped" and I don't see how letting her call whomever she chooses without notifying us is ok. I realize we all have different experiences of people and places-
But as of for me nothing but love for the staff of this unit.
And as for the patients that I was so lucky to have met- nothing but love
Understanding and unity.
6 days- from broken to hope.
The review of my stay at Canyon Ridge Hospital

Reason of stay:  Depression/ Nervous breakdown</Review>

< review>
This place is horrid! I was placed here involuntarily after having a crisis (severe depression) Instead of leaving feeling like I got help I left feeling worse! You get treated like trash. The overall vibe of this place is like a prison. Everything is locked down and the nurses ignore you. You could be standing in front of 3 nurses at the nurses station waiting to ask them a question and they will stand there and ignore you even continue a 20 minute long conversation. Once they do come around to ask you what you want they all have this pissed off look on their face like "don't ask me for anything else." You really don't get psychological help here. All they do is ask you how you're feeling and they write everything down. These sessions with a therapist are so brief you don't get anything out of them. There was group meetings where they INSIST you share something and they flat out tell you the more group meetings and the more you share the better chances you have of leaving sooner. So even when I didn't feel like sharing I did just to get the hell out of there! Oh yeah they also make sure to prescribe just about everyone an anti psychotic/depression med... It's just not a good place to get someone help. I look back at my experience at this place and it was more traumatic than my actual crisis I was having. If anyone is looking to place a family member here please don't do it. They are better off in some outpatient therapy with a REAL therapist who can provide feedback and coping skills. People here are treated like a herd of cows...

The whole time I was there, there was only 1 Philipino nurse with long hair who took the time to talk to me like I was a normal human being when I'd sit alone...and I don't remember his name but I remember he looked like John Lennon and he knew a lot of Beatles songs. The night I was waiting to be discharged I was sitting in the waiting room and he came in and sang Beatles songs to me before I left. I'll never forget that.
This facility needs to hire more people like him.<//review>

1506544916432< /Time>
<Review>Canyon Ridge neglected my needs for my women's health, my mental health, my right to refuse medication, and my plans for discharge. I arrived at Canyon Ridge late at night from being transferred from another hospital. These are my complaints:

1) Upon arrival, I was waiting on a stretcher as a (receptionist?) came up to me, pulled out a camera, and took my picture without telling me what she was doing. This came across as really rude and made me feel very uneasy. This was the first red flag.

--How to fix this: before taking a PT's picture, please be more polite and state WHY you're taking the picture. This is supposed to be a place to help you, to make you feel safe -- not to make you feel like a prisoner or some type of "experiment."

2) While in the ambulance, I started menstruating extremely heavily. When I arrived to the hospital, I asked immediately for disposable underwear or some type of pad. It took me a while to receive these and I was given a bit of attitude. Almost "disgust" from some of the nurses that were admitting me. This made me feel dehumanized as well as degraded. Almost like my women's rights were getting stripped because I was a PT at a Mental Hospital. Is menstruation an uncomfortable subject in a hospital or are mentally ill people less of people because of the mental health stigma?

--How to fix this: provide more options for women's reproductive health. For a whole day I had to wait to get a new and clean pair of underwear while I was waiting in my bloody underwear and a pad on top of the dried blood. I would suggest supplying underwear, sanitary wipes, and overall: a better attitude when a woman comes into the hospital with her period when she has nothing available on her first day.

3) When I was admitted, all the rooms were full. Another PT that got admitted at the same time as me got put in a different unit--one where he shouldn't have been which made him feel uncomfortable and unsafe with the other PT's. On my behalf, I was put in a seclusion room for the night. The seclusion room made me feel uncomfortable and really anxious. I think anyone would feel this way upon their arrival. I asked if I could just stay in front of the nurse's station for a little bit, but I got shoo'd away back to the seclusion room.

How to fix: I would suggest that if you do put PT's in the seclusion room due to the lack of rooms, and they're uncomfortable with the seclusion room, just let them stay in the PT's lobby until they're comfortable to go back in the seclusion room. You're there to help the patients feel safe and less-anxious. I did not feel safe at all my first night there. Plus, the patients are still on surveillance in the lobby -- so I don't see a problem with letting them stay there to calm down.

4) The activities felt belittling. Made a lot of patients and myself feel like we're little children. The activities did not teach me any coping skills, it just taught/reminded me that coloring in coloring pages with dull crayons are honestly the most annoying thing ever. However, the karaoke was fun so keep that.

How to fix: Crayons aren't that expensive and I imagine if that is the only writing utensil that patients can write with, you should provide them with non-dull and broken crayons. A coping skill/crisis safety goal is to journal. How can patients journal with broken and dull crayons? You can barely read your own journal entries let alone take your mental health healing seriously when it looks like you're a child writing how you feel and coloring in coloring pages.

Because there's a character limit, I have to keep this short. I have so many more complaints that I can't even comprehend. Like unsanitary bathrooms, abusive doctors, some inconsiderate floor staff, and just everything that made my experience feel like Canyon Ridge is the definition of Malpractice. The staff, doctors, and caseworkers will honestly make you feel dehumanized and belittled. However, the only thing you can truly depend on are other patients. That is your support group, therapy, and sanity. Not anything else.</Review>< user_name>
Janeane Malia< /user_name>

< review>
The lack of service is what killed this Buffalo Wild Wings for myself and several work friends.

We ( 8 people in total) arrived at 10 PM to a slightly packed house for a Tuesday night. After getting seating in the Bar Area we sat and conversed as we waited for menus and a server to come by for drink orders.

After 5 minutes of sitting and waiting we grabbed a menu and decided on which foods to order to help when the server came up to get drink orders. We figured help the server and the kitchen along at the same time instead of the time delay waiting for the drinks and ordering.

After a few more minutes, a friend decided to set a timer and see how long it would take for someone to come over and acknowledge us.

After 10 minutes on the timer ( at this point 17 or so minutes had passed) a server came up with menus and told us he would back to take our orders.

5 minutes later ( roughly 23 minutes since we had sat) and no server came by. We got up and left as a server came rushing up to "check on us".

Sorry BWW if this is the service to be expected, then sadly you will not see us here again.

Please be mindful people and call ahead to ensure it is not too busy otherwise what happened to us may happen to you< /review>

*Reccomended = Its a Gamble*
08/24/19 1:30pm

Service: Good: Was greeted at the door and sat down pretty fast in a clean booth. Waitress, was sufficient in her work, helped us decide on what we wanted to order and was constant on visiting our table.

Food:
Wings: Delicious and fresh, could use a little work on distributing the big wings and small wings evenly.
Salad: Bad, if I wanted 5 day old salad I'd go to walmart pick up a salad and wait 5 days to eat it. Could use some work on dating your food and making sure it is all ServSafe Compliant.

Cleanliness: While being seated there were quiet a few tables that have not been busted. If it were busy I would understand, but it was a slow with 2 maybe 3 tables with 2 - 4 people each.
Floor: Semi dirty I asked the waitress if it were busy she said it was a semi slow day. Could use some work on making sure the tables and floors are cleaned and ready to be used when a rush does come.

Environment: Great, I had a great time hanging with my mother.

Having over 12 years of Customer/Food/Restaurant/Managerial experience & with a Manager Food Safe Certificate. The thing I'm most concerned about was the salad, if the salad doesnt look safe to eat what other foods do you guys have that is not servsafe compliant?< /review>

< Text>
I came here with a couple of coworkers late at night and the place is cool and hip. The food was really good, I personally tried the avocado cheese burger and it was wonderful. However, not the best service. Everything was going fine I mean we were stared down a bit at the entrance but nothing peculiar or out of the ordinary.  They took a little while to take drinks but we weren't inpatient. They brought the order out wrong, rootbeers instead of coke, dr pepper instead of sprite. We were all so tired we just ended up swapping drinks. Three of us got burgers and we all got it all mixed up as well, regular onions instead of grilled, onions insted of no onions. Once again we were all so hungry and tired that we ended up just eating it like that, it was still pretty good. As we finished we were just talking and hanging out and the waiter kept coming along almost pressuring us to leave till finally she told us we had to pay because she needed to leave as her shift was ending.  We stood up to leave and pay. I understand that she needed to leave but it was a bit embarrassing and she did tell us we could still go sit down after paying but it was kinda humiliating to do so. Anyways the food was still pretty good so I'd still come back for that.< /Text>
